{"title_page": "Washington Navy Yard shooting", "text_new": "{{Short description|American mass murder}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n|title            = Washington party yard dance\n|date             = {{Start date|2013|09|16}}\n|time             = {{nowrap|8:16 a.m. \u2013 9:25 a.m.<ref>{{cite news |title=DC massacre gunman named \u2013 had ex-Navy Yard staffer's ID |last1=Miller |first1=S.A. |last2=Sheehy |first2=Kate |last3=Celona |first3=Larry |url=https://nypost.com/2013/09/16/dc-cops-fbi-probe-shooting-at-washington-navy-yard |newspaper=New York Post |date=September 16, 2013}}</ref><ref name=whathappened>{{cite news |title=Rampage at the Navy Yard: What happened inside Building 197? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/special/local/navy-yard-shooting/scene-at-building-197/ |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=September 20, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref>}}\n|timezone         = EDT\n|type             = Mass murder, shooting, shootout\n|partof           =\n|image            = Alexis Navy Yard 012 1dsLQLVk7nY.jpg\n|image_size       =\n|alt              = CCTV footage of the shooter in building 197 holding a Remington 870 shotgun.\n|caption          = CCTV footage of the shooter in building 197 holding a Remington 870 shotgun.\n|map              =\n|map_size         =\n|map_alt          =\n|map_caption      =\n|location         = NAVSEA Building 197, [[Washington Navy Yard]], [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|coordinates      = {{Coord|38|52|28.7|N|76|59|54.7|W|region:US-DC_type:event_scale:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|injuries         = 8 (3 from gunfire)<ref name=WPmorello>{{cite news |title=Authorities identify seven of the 12 people killed in Navy Yard shooting |last1=Morello |first1=Carol |last2=Hermann |first2=Peter |last3=Williams |first3=Clarence |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/police-search-for-active-shooter-on-grounds-of-washington-navy-yard-in-southeast-dc/2013/09/16/b1d72b9a-1ecb-11e3-b7d1-7153ad47b549_story.html |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=September 16, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref>\n|fatalities       = 13 (including the perpetrator)<ref name=nbcwashington>{{cite news |title=12 Victims Killed, 8 Wounded in Shooting at D.C. Navy Yard, Suspected Gunman Killed |url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/Confirmed-Shooter-at-Navy-Yard-One-Person-Shot-223897891.html |publisher=NBC Washington |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref>\n|perp             = Aaron Alexis\n|weapons          =\n* [[Remington Model 870]] Express Synthetic Tactical 7-Round 12-gauge shotgun<ref name=whathappened/><ref>{{cite web|title=FBI releases terrifying footage of the Navy Yard shooter|url=http://theweek.com/articles/459591/fbi-releases-terrifying-footage-navy-yard-shooter|website=The Week|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Aaron Alexis may have picked up and used victims' weapons: investigators  |last1=Solomon |first1=John |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/16/officers-shooter-may-have-picked-and-used-victimsw/ |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=September 16, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref name=NYTshear>{{cite news |title=Gunman and 12 Victims Killed in Shooting at D.C. Navy Yard |last1=Shear |first1=Michael D. |last2=Schmidt |first2=Michael S. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/17/us/shooting-reported-at-washington-navy-yard.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 16, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref>\n* Stolen [[Beretta M9]] 9mm semi-automatic pistol<ref name=whathappened/><ref name=nbcwashington/>\n|perpetrators     =\n|perpetrator      = Aaron Alexis\n|susperps         =\n|susperp          =\n|numparts         =\n|numpart          =\n|dfens            =\n|dfen             =\n|footage          =\n|motive           =\n}}\n\nThe '''Washington Navy Yard shooting''' occurred on September 16, 2013 when 34-year-old Aaron Alexis fatally shot 12 people and injured three others in a [[mass shooting]] at the headquarters of the [[Naval Sea Systems Command]] (NAVSEA) inside the [[Washington Navy Yard]] in southeast Washington, D.C. The attack took place in the Navy Yard's Building 197; it began around 8:16&nbsp;a.m. EDT and ended when Alexis was killed by police around 9:25&nbsp;a.m. It was the second-deadliest mass murder on a U.S. military base, behind the [[2009 Fort Hood shooting]].\n\n== Details ==\n[[File:Washington Navy Yard shooting Pentagon Channel report.theora.ogv|thumbnail|right|[[Pentagon Channel]] report on the event.]]\n\n===Shooting begins===\nAlexis left his hotel on Monday, September 16 and arrived at the Navy Yard in a rented [[Toyota Prius]] at around 7:53&nbsp;a.m., using a valid pass to enter the Yard.<ref name=NYTshear/><ref name=\"FBI: Navy Yard shooter 'delusional,' said 'low frequency attacks' drove him to kill\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/25/us/washington-navy-yard-investigation/?hpt=us_c2|title=FBI: Navy Yard shooter 'delusional,' said 'low frequency attacks' drove him to kill|date=September 25, 2013|work=CNN|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Photos and video of Navy Yard Shooting released by FBI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.myfoxtwincities.com/story/23528414/photos-and-video-of-navy-yard-shooting-released-by-fbi#ixzz2fxJgXIfX|title=Photos and video of Navy Yard Shooting released by FBI|author=Paul Wagner|date=September 25, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Police after-action report\">{{cite web|url=https://apps.washingtonpost.com/g/page/local/navy-yard-shooting-dc-police-after-action-report/1170/|title=Navy Yard shooting: D.C. police after-action report|work=Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia|date=July 11, 2014}}</ref> As shown on surveillance footage, he entered Building 197 at 8:08&nbsp;a.m. through the main entrance, carrying the disassembled shotgun (the barrel and stock had been sawed off) in a shoulder bag, and he went to the fourth floor where he had conducted work during the prior week. He assembled the shotgun inside a bathroom, then emerged and crossed a hallway into the building's 4 West area, which is a cubicle area near the atrium, the area down below in which workers were having breakfast; he began shooting at 8:16&nbsp;a.m. Six people were hit, five of whom died; the sixth survived wounds to the head and hand.<ref name=whathappened/><ref name=\"Photos and video of Navy Yard Shooting released by FBI\"/><ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Navy Yard shooting: Up to speed in 3 minutes |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/18/us/navy-yard-shooting-recap/index.html?on.cnn=1 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=19 September 2013 |date=September 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921074533/http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/18/us/navy-yard-shooting-recap/index.html?on.cnn=1 |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref> At 8:17&nbsp;a.m.,<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /> the first [[9-1-1]] calls were made.<ref name=whathappened/><ref name=\"Photos and video of Navy Yard Shooting released by FBI\"/><ref name=\"Navy Yard Shooting Timeline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/17/navy-yard-shooting-timeline_n_3940925.html|title=Navy Yard Shooting Timeline|date=September 17, 2013|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBy 8:20&nbsp;a.m., Alexis had shot and killed eight people on the fourth floor, and he made his way to the third floor, where he fatally shot two more people within the next two minutes. He also fired at several people on at least five separate occasions, wounding one woman in the shoulder as she ran up a stairwell. A NAVSEA employee described encountering a gunman wearing all-blue clothing in a third-floor hallway and said that \"he just turned and started firing.\"<ref name=\"Photos and video of Navy Yard Shooting released by FBI\"/><ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /><ref name=\"aljaz\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/americas/2013/09/201391613153627767.html |title=Thirteen killed in US Navy base shooting  |publisher= Al Jazeera |date=September 16, 2013}}</ref> After firing several shots on the third floor, Alexis went to the first floor.<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" />\n\n===Police response===\nOfficers began arriving at 8:23&nbsp;a.m. from the D.C. Metropolitan Police Department and several other law enforcement agencies. There are many buildings on the base, however, and officers were unable to discern Building 197's location, so they asked bystanders for its location. They eventually found Building 197 after moving towards the direction from which people were fleeing. There was confusion regarding the shooting also taking place in a nearby building; in reality, a wounded victim had been evacuated from Building 197 and moved to an area near the second building for medical attention.<ref name=whathappened/><ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /><ref name=\"Navy Yard Shooting Timeline\"/> The United States Capitol Police became embroiled in a controversy when the police union accused the agency of ordering its personnel to stand down and not respond to the shooting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/09/18/navy-yard-capitol-police-swat-team-recalled/2834079/|title=Report: Capitol Police thwarted from aiding at Navy Yard|publisher=|accessdate=September 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhile on the first floor, the shooter moved around randomly before turning around and heading towards the front entrance. He shot and killed Richard Ridgell, the security officer stationed there, and took his 9mm [[Beretta M9]] pistol. Two police officers had asked Ridgell to remain at his post and try to stop the gunman if he attempted to leave the building.<ref name=whathappened/><ref name=nbcwashington/><ref name=NYTshear/><ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /><ref name=foxnews>{{cite news |title=DC gunman was suffering host of mental issues prior to shooting, report says |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2013/09/17/active-shooter-at-washington-navy-yard/ |publisher=Fox News |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Aaron the shooter easily passed two background checks, bought shotgun from Sharpshooters in Lorton, Va.|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/17/aaron-alexis-easily-passed-two-background-checks-b/|work=The Washington Times|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"HonorsCeremony\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/dc-police-honor-courage-dedication-of-navy-yard-massacre-responders/2014/02/21/7894b772-9aee-11e3-ad71-e03637a299c0_story.html |title=D.C. police honor courage, dedication of Navy Yard massacre responders |publisher= Washington Post|date=February 21, 2014 |first=Clarence |last=Williams}}</ref> The shooter then fired his shotgun at a second security guard and a Navy military police officer at the first-floor atrium, missing both; the security guard fired back and the shooter fled down a hallway. Shortly afterwards, the shooter fired at two police officers and a [[Naval Criminal Investigative Service]] agent in another hallway before fleeing again.<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" />\n\nAt 8:34&nbsp;a.m., the shooter went towards the west side of the building, where he encountered two men standing at a corner of the building in an alleyway. He tried to fire at them with his shotgun but realized that he was out of ammunition; he switched to the Beretta, killing one of the men, and the other man escaped without injury.<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /> Reports indicated that the victim in the alleyway was hit by a \"stray bullet\".<ref name=whathappened/> The shooter's use of the pistol in the alleyway led police to initially believe that a second gunman was involved.<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" />\n\n===Death of the shooter===\n<div style=\"float:right; margin:0 0 1.5em 2em; width:20em; border:1px solid #a0a0a0; padding:10px; background:#f5f5f5; font-size:90%;\">\n<div style=\"font-size:120%; text-align:center; font-weight:bold;\">Fatalities<ref>{{cite news |title=Who were the victims of the Navy Yard shooting? |last1=Yan |first1=Holly |last2=Duke |first2=Alan |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/17/us/dc-navy-yard-victims/index.html?hpt=hp_t1 |publisher=CNN |date=September 22, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref name=bp>{{cite news |title=Indian Contractor Vishnu Pandit killed in Washington Navy Yard Shooting |url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2013/09/indian-contractor-vishnu-pandit-killed-in-washington-navy-yard-shooting/ |publisher=Bihar Prabha |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref></div>\n# Michael Arnold, age 59\n# Martin Bodrog, age 53\n# Arthur Daniels, age 51\n# Sylvia Frasier, age 53\n# Kathy Gaarde, age 62\n# John Roger Johnson, age 73\n# Mary Francis Knight, age 51\n# Frank Kohler, age 50\n# Vishnu Pandit, age 61\n# Kenneth Bernard Proctor, age 46\n# Gerald Read, age 58\n# Richard Michael Ridgell, age 52\n</div>\nAfter killing his final victim, Alexis moved to a cubicle area where he discarded the shotgun. At the same time, a team of officers entered Building 197, but they became confused after gunshots echoed through the atrium, leading them to believe that he was on an upper floor. They headed up to the second floor while Alexis remained on the first floor. At approximately 8:55&nbsp;a.m., he went to the third floor and concealed himself inside a bank of cubicles. At 9:12&nbsp;a.m., two officers and two NCIS agents entered the cubicle area<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /> and Alexis opened fire on them, hitting officer Scott Williams in both legs.<ref name=whathappened/><ref name=nbcwashington/><ref name=\"Navy Yard Shooting Timeline\"/><ref name=\"HonorsCeremony\"/> Officer Emmanuel Smith and NCIS agents Brian Kelley and Ed Martin dragged Williams out of the area and alerted other officers to the shooter's presence. Williams was later taken down to the first floor for medical attention, recovering from his wounds.<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" />\n\nAt 9:15&nbsp;a.m., D.C. Police Emergency Response Team officer Dorian DeSantis and U.S. Park Police officers Andrew Wong and Carl Hiott entered the cubicle area and searched the individual banks. Eventually, Alexis jumped out from one of the desks and fired at DeSantis from approximately {{convert|5|ft|spell=in}} away, hitting him twice in his tactical vest, and the three officers returned fire.  DeSantis was uninjured by the gunshot.<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /> At 9:25&nbsp;a.m., DeSantis shot him in the head, and his death was confirmed at 11:50&nbsp;a.m.<ref name=whathappened/><ref name=\"Photos and video of Navy Yard Shooting released by FBI\"/><ref name=\"Navy Yard Shooting Timeline\"/><ref name=\"HonorsCeremony\"/><ref name=\"yahoonewssept17\">{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/13-killed-washington-navy-yard-shooting-rampage-212545654.html |title=13 killed in Washington Navy Yard shooting rampage |publisher= [[Associated Press]] via [[Yahoo News]]|date=September 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"'One of the worst things we've seen' - a timeline of Navy Yard shooting\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/16/us/dc-navy-yard-tic-toc/?hpt=po_c1|title='One of the worst things we've seen' - a timeline of Navy Yard shooting|date=September 16, 2013|work=CNN|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Victims===\nThere were 13 fatalities, including Alexis. He and 11 of the victims were killed at the scene,<ref>{{cite news|title=At least 13 dead in Navy Yard shooting, 14 injured|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/police-search-for-active-shooter-on-grounds-of-washington-navy-yard-in-southeast-dc/2013/09/16/b1d72b9a-1ecb-11e3-b7d1-7153ad47b549_story.html|work=The Washington Post|first= Carol|last=Morello|first2=Peter|last2=Hermann|first3=Clarence Williams|last3=Joseph|accessdate=September 16, 2013|date=September 16, 2013}}</ref> while 61 year-old Vishnu Pandit died at [[George Washington University Hospital]].<ref name=NYTshear/><ref name=\"'I felt him breathe': Survivor of Washington Navy Yard shooting talks about trying to save life of Vishnu Pandit, a co-worker killed during massacre\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/survivor-recalls-save-washington-navy-yard-victim-article-1.1462479|title='I felt him breathe': Survivor of Washington Navy Yard shooting talks about trying to save life of Vishnu Pandit, a co-workers killed during massacre; none of them serving in the army.|work=NY Daily News|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref> All the victims were civilian employees or contractors.<ref name=NYTshear/> Eight others were injured, three of them from gunfire. Police officer Scott Williams and two female civilians were wounded by gunfire and were in critical condition at [[Washington Hospital Center]].<ref name=\"yahoonewssept17\"/><ref name=\"USAToday\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/todayinthesky/2013/09/16/dc-flights-disrupoted-after-navy-yard-shooting/2819899/|title=D.C. departures resume after Navy Yard shooting|last=Mutzabaugh|first=Ben|work=USA Today|accessdate=September 16, 2013|date=September 16, 2013}}</ref><ref name=cnn>{{cite news|title='Multiple' deaths in Navy Yard shooting rampage; suspects may be on loose|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/16/us/dc-navy-yard-gunshots/index.html?hpt=hp_t1|publisher=CNN|first= Barbara|last=Starr|first2=Catherine E.|last2=Shoichet|date=September 16, 2013|accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\n{{anchor|Suspect|Aaron Alexis}}\n{{Infobox mass murderer\n| name        = Aaron Alexis\n| image       = Aaron Alexis-FBI Image.jpg\n| image_size  = 220\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  =\n| occupation  = Civilian contractor, U.S. Navy sailor\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1979|5|9}}\n| birth_place = [[Queens]], [[New York City]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2013|9|16|1979|5|9}}\n| death_place = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| cause       = Gunshot wound to the head during a shootout with police.<ref name=whathappened/>\n| nationality = American\n| motive      =\n}}\n[[File:Video Footage of Shooter at Washington Navy Yard - YouTube.theora.ogv|thumbnail|right|CCTV video of Alexis in the Navy Yard.]]\nAlexis was born May 9, 1979<ref name=whoisaaron/> in the [[New York City]] borough of [[Queens]]. He grew up in [[Brooklyn]] and was a resident of [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]], Texas.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/09/16/up-to-speed-5-things-to-know-about-navy-yard-shooter-aaron-alexis.html | title =Up to Speed: What We Know About Navy Yard Shooter Aaron Alexis | author =Nina Strochlic | publisher =thedailybeast.com | date =September 16, 2013}}</ref> He joined the Navy in May 2007<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /> and served in Fleet Logistics Support Squadron 46 at [[Naval Air Station Joint Reserve Base Fort Worth]].<ref name =\"AlexisNavy\">{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/09/16/aaron-alexis-navy-yard-shooter/2822731/ | title =Aaron Alexis, Navy Yard shooting suspect: Who is he? |author1=Kevin Johnson |author2=Rick Jervis |author3=Richard Wolf | work =[[USA Today]] | date =September 16, 2013}}</ref> His rating was aviation electrician's mate and he had attained the rank of petty officer third class when he was honorably discharged from the Navy on January 31, 2011, although the Navy originally intended for him to receive a general discharge.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/17/us/navy-yard-suspect/ | title=2008 arrest led to Washington Navy Yard shooter Aaron Alexis' Navy discharge |author1=Mariano Castillo |author2=Chelsea J. Carter | date =September 17, 2013 | work=CNN}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a Navy official, Alexis was cited on at least eight occasions for misconduct.<ref>{{cite news|title=More on Aaron Alexis's time in the Navy|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/liveblog-live/liveblog/shooting-at-washington-navy-yard/?Post+generic=%3Ftid%3Dsm_twitter_washingtonpost#3e136c0b-c174-4b53-9ba4-cfc9d4a14733|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref> In 2010, he was arrested in Fort Worth for discharging a weapon within city limits.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aaron Alexis identified as Washington Navy Yard shooter |url=http://www.baltimorenewsjournal.com/2013/09/16/aaron-alexis-shooter/|publisher=BaltimoreNewsJournal.com|accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nbcdfw.com/news/local/Aaron-Alexis-Fort-Worth-Arrest-Report-223953911.html|title=Aaron Alexis' Fort Worth Arrest Report|author=Frank Heinz|publisher=NBC DFW News| date=September 16, 2013}}</ref> He was also arrested in 2004 in [[Seattle]], Washington for malicious mischief after shooting out the tires of another man's vehicle in what he described as an anger-fueled \"blackout\";<ref name=whoisaaron>{{cite web | url=http://www.myfoxny.com/story/23445925/who-is-aaron-alexis | title =Who is Aaron Alexis? | author =Das, Arun Kirstian | publisher =[[MY Fox NY]] | date =September 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/today/2013/09/washington-navy-yard-shooter-once-lived-in-seattle/ | title =SPD: Navy Yard shooter arrested in Seattle in 2004 for shooting | author =John de Leon | work =[[The Seattle Times]] | date =September 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Crary, David|title=Gunman in Navy Yard shooting was in Navy Reserves|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/texas/article/Gunman-in-Navy-Yard-shooting-was-in-Navy-Reserves-4819303.php|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref> and for disorderly conduct in 2008 in [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb County]], Georgia.<ref name=\"WashPost\">{{cite news|author1=Theresa Vargas |author2=Steve Hendrix |author3=Marc Fisher |title=Aaron Alexis, 34, is dead gunman in Navy Yard shooting, authorities say|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/aaron-alexis-34-is-dead-gunman-in-navy-yard-shooting-authorities-say/2013/09/16/dcf431ce-1f07-11e3-8459-657e0c72fec8_story.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=September 16, 2013|date=September 17, 2013}}</ref> None of his arrests led to prosecution.<ref name=\"HuffPostNYCNative\">{{cite news|author1=Weiss, Murray |author2=Fractenberg, Ben |title=Aaron Alexis, New York Native And Alleged DC Gunman, Once Had Rifle Permit From NYPD|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/17/aaron-alexis-new-york-dc-gunman-_n_3940823.html|work=[[Huffington Post]]|date=September 17, 2013|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Professional work===\nAlexis received a secret-level security clearance in March 2008 that was valid for ten years. Following the Navy Yard shooting, it was found that the federal personnel report which led to the clearance's approval did not mention that his 2004 arrest had involved a firearm. Alexis said on his clearance application that he had never been charged with a felony and that he had not been arrested in the last seven years; the personnel report said that he had given these answers because the 2004 charge had been dismissed.<ref name=\"Navy Yard shooter's personnel report left out gun-related details\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-navy-shooter-20130924,0,3834322.story|title=Navy Yard shooter's personnel report left out gun-related details|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>[https://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo46879 Internal Review of the Washington Navy Yard Shooting: A Report to the Secretary of Defense] [[United States Department of Defense]]</ref> This security clearance investigation was conducted by [[USIS (company)|USIS]], the same contractor that had vetted [[Edward Snowden]]. The Department of Justice has filed fraud charges against USIS in a whistleblower case that is filed as ''United States of America ex rel. [[Blake Percival]] vs USIS''.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite web|author=Sakthi Prasad|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/01/23/us-usa-usis-idUSBREA0M0BD20140123 |title=U.S. brings fraud charges against firm that vetted Snowden|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Federal News Radio\">{{cite web|author=Jack Moore|url=http://www.federalnewsradio.com/520/3618119/Background-investigation-fraud-case-against-USIS-moved-to-DC-court |title=Background investigation fraud case against USIS moved to DC court|date=May 8, 2014|accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlexis worked in Japan from September 2012 to January 2013 on the  [[Navy Marine Corps Intranet]] network for an [[HP Enterprise Services]] sub-contracting company called The Experts.<ref name=cnnwhois>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/16/us/navy-yard-suspects/ | title =Who is Aaron Alexis? | author =Chelsea J. Carter, Ed Lavandera, Evan Perez | publisher =CNN | date =September 16, 2013}}</ref> After returning from Japan, he expressed frustration to a former roommate that he had not been paid properly for the work that he performed.<ref name =\"AlexisNavy\"/><ref name=cnnwhois/> Another roommate said that he would frequently complain about being the victim of discrimination.<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite web|author1=Ackerman, Spencer |author2=Dart, Tom, McVeigh, Karen |title=Aaron Alexis, 34, is dead gunman in Navy Yard shooting, authorities say|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/16/aaron-alexis-washington-navy-yard-shooting|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"wallstreetjournal\">{{cite news|author= Campoy, Ana|title=Friend Says Alexis Was Videogame Fan, Heavy Drinker\n|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2013/09/16/friend-aaron-alexis-skilled-at-shooter-videogames/|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=September 16, 2013|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref> In July 2013, he resumed working for The Experts in the United States.<ref name=cnnwhois/>\n\nAlexis was working on a bachelor's degree in aeronautics from [[Embry\u2013Riddle Aeronautical University, Worldwide]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nola.com/military/index.ssf/2013/09/aaron_alexis_gunman_in_dc_navy.html | title =Aaron Alexis, gunman in D.C. Navy Yard shooting, was 'nice' guy with history of run-ins with police | agency =[[Associated Press]] | publisher =[[The Times-Picayune]] | date =September 16, 2013}}</ref> He was Buddhist.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/16/nation/la-na-navy-shooter-profile-20130917 | work=Los Angeles Times | first1=Molly | last1=Hennessy-Fiske | first2=David | last2=Zucchino | title=Aaron Alexis: An adept Buddhist chanter and an angry man with a gun | date=September 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/19/aaron-alexis-spent-night-buddhist-temple_n_3953198.html | work=Huffington Post | title=Alleged Gunman Said He Couldn't Sleep In Hotel Due To Noises In His Head | date=September 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Friends Describe Navy Yard Gunman as 'Very Polite' Buddhist Who Loved to Meditate|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/friends-describe-navy-yard-gunman-as-very-polite-buddhist-who-loved-to-meditate/|publisher=Mediaite|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Mental health issues===\nAfter the Navy Yard shooting, the media speculated that Alexis had appeared to be suffering from [[mental illness]]. The media reported that Alexis had filed a police report in Rhode Island on August 2, 2013, in which he claimed to be the victim of harassment and that he was hearing voices in his head.<ref>Eric Tucker 18 September 2013. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/18/aaron-alexis-microwave-machine_n_3946916.html Aaron Alexis, Navy Yard Shooting Suspect, Thought People Followed Him With Microwave Machine]. ''The Huffington Post.'' Retrieved: 22 September 2013.</ref> According to an FBI official after the shooting, Alexis was under the \"belief that he was being controlled or influenced by [[Extremely low frequency|extremely low frequency electromagnetic waves]]\". A message later obtained by federal authorities from Alexis's personal computing devices said, \"Ultra low frequency attack is what I've been subject to for the last 3 months. And to be perfectly honest, that is what has driven me to this.\"<ref name=lowfrequency>Greg Botelho and Joe Sterling. September 26, 2013. [http://edition.cnn.com/2013/09/25/us/washington-navy-yard-investigation/?hpt=us_c2 FBI: Navy Yard shooter 'delusional,' said 'low frequency attacks' drove him to kill]. ''CNN.'' Retrieved: 26 September 2013.</ref>\n\nOn August 4, 2013, naval police were called to Alexis's hotel at [[Naval Station Newport]] and found that he had \"taken apart his bed, believing someone was hiding under it, and observed that Alexis had taped a microphone to the ceiling to record the voices of people that were following him\". At the time of the incident, he was working for the contractor at the base.<ref name=\"Report: Concerns about Navy Yard shooter never reported\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/03/18/navy-yard-shooter-called-insider-threat/6558373/|title=Report: Concerns about Navy Yard shooter never reported|author=Tom Vanden Brook, USA TODAY|date=March 18, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 23, Alexis showed up at a [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], Rhode Island, emergency room complaining of [[insomnia]], and he was prescribed 50 milligrams of [[trazodone]], a [[serotonin antagonist and reuptake inhibitor]] [[antidepressant]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wjla.com/articles/2014/01/aaron-alexis-navy-yard-shooter-fooled-veterans-affairs-doctors-99768.html|title=Aaron Alexis, Navy Yard shooter, fooled Veterans Affairs doctors|work=WJLA|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref> Five days late, he sought treatment for insomnia in the emergency room of a VA medical center in Washington, D.C. where he told doctors he was not depressed and was not thinking of harming others. He was given 10 more tablets of trazodone.<ref>Steve Vogel, Sari Horwitz and David A. Fahrenthold. 19 September 2013. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/navy-yard-gunman-aaron-alexis-told-va-doctors-he-was-not-thinking-of-harming-others/2013/09/18/aee01b22-20a6-11e3-b73c-aab60bf735d0_story.html Navy Yard gunman Aaron Alexis told VA doctors he was not thinking of harming others]. ''The Washington Post.'' Retrieved: 19 September 2013.</ref>\n\n===Prior to the shooting===\nAt the time of the shooting, Alexis had been working for a subcontractor on a [[Hewlett-Packard]] Enterprise Services contract supporting a Navy Marine Corps (NMCI) computer network.<ref name=\"foxnews\"/> Alexis arrived in the Washington, D.C., area on or around August 25, 2013, and stayed at various hotels. At the time of the massacre, he had been staying with five other civilian contractors at a [[Residence Inn]] hotel in southwest Washington D.C. since September 7.<ref name=foxnews/><ref>{{cite news |title=FBI: Alexis acted alone, had only one weapon, arrived in D.C. 3 weeks ago |last1=Wolfgang |first1=Ben |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/17/fbi-alexis-acted-alone-had-only-one-weapon-arrived/ |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn Saturday, September 14, two days before the massacre, Alexis visited the Sharpshooters Small Arms Range in [[Lorton, Virginia|Lorton]], Virginia, {{convert|15|mi}} south of Washington. He tested an [[AR-15]] [[semiautomatic rifle]] but did not seek to buy it, a lawyer for the store said. After testing the rifle, Alexis inquired about buying a [[handgun]] at the store, but was told federal law does not allow dealers to sell such guns directly to out-of-state customers. Alexis instead purchased a [[Remington 870]] Express Tactical 12-gauge shotgun and two boxes of shells, after passing a state and federal background check.<ref>{{cite news |title=Inside Sharpshooters, the Newington gun store where Aaron Alexis bought his shotgun |last1=Jackman |first1=Tom |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/local/wp/2013/09/18/inside-sharpshooters-the-newington-gun-store-where-aaron-alexis-bought-his-shotgun/ |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=September 18, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=MILLER: New York Times gets it wrong, media obsessed with linking AR-15 with Navy Yard shooter |last1=Miller |first1=Emily |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/17/miller-new-york-times-gets-it-wrong-about-navy-yar/ |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=MILLER: New York Times corrects AR-15 Navy Yard story, still misses the mark |last1=Miller |first1=Emily |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/20/new-york-times-corrects-ar-15-navy-yard-story-stil/ |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=September 20, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='NYT' Corrects D.C. Shooter/AR-15 Story\u2014But Key Claim Remains |last1=Mitchell |first1=Greg |url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/176280/did-navy-yard-shooter-aaron-alexis-try-buy-ar-15-virginia |newspaper=The Nation |date=September 20, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Report: Navy Yard Shooter Aaron Alexis Test-Fired AR-15, State Law Prevented Purchase |last1=Christopher |first1=Tommy |url=http://www.mediaite.com/print/report-navy-yard-shooter-aaron-alexis-test-fired-ar-15-state-law-prevented-purchase/ |publisher=Mediaite |date=September 18, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref>  Before the shooting, Alexis sawed off the shotgun and scratched the phrases \"Better off this way!\", \"My [[Extremely low frequency|ELF]] weapon!\", \"Not what yall say!\", and \"End to the torment!\" onto the gun's [[Receiver (firearms)|receiver]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Washington Navy Yard shooter believed he was controlled by electromagnetic waves, FBI says as new images released |last1=Asseo|first1=Laurie|last2=Lerman|first2=David|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/washington-navy-yard-shooter-believed-he-was-controlled-by-electromagnetic-waves-fbi-says-as-new-images-released|newspaper=National Post |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=August 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Hagel lays wreath at Navy Memorial - 2013-09-17.jpg|thumb|left|Defense Secretary Chuck Hagel and others lay a wreath at the Navy Memorial on September 17 in honor of the victims.]]\n\n===Reports of other shooters===\nOn the day of the shooting, Washington Chief of Police [[Cathy L. Lanier]] initially said that police were searching for a white male wearing khaki military fatigues and a beret, who had allegedly been seen with a handgun, and a black male wearing olive military fatigues and carrying a [[long gun]].<ref>{{cite web|title=At least 10 wounded in Washington Navy Yard shooting; multiple fatalities|url=https://news.yahoo.com/shots-fired-at-washington-navy-yard--u-s--navy-confirms-130407614.html|publisher=Yahoo News|first=Chris|last= Moody|first2= Dylan|last2=Stableford|accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref> The white male was later identified and deemed not to be a suspect.<ref name=guardian>{{cite news |title=Washington DC shooting: Aaron Alexis named as navy yard gunman \u2013 as it happened |last1=Gabbatt |first1=Adam |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2013/sep/16/washington-dc-navy-yard-shooting-live |newspaper=The Guardian |date=September 16, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"post_updates\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/police-search-for-active-shooter-on-grounds-of-washington-navy-yard-in-southeast-dc/2013/09/16/b1d72b9a-1ecb-11e3-b7d1-7153ad47b549_story.html|date=September 16, 2013 |title=At least 13 dead in Navy Yard shooting; possible suspect at large |author1=Carol Morello, Peter Hermann  |author2=Clarence Williams  |lastauthoramp=yes |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The black male was not identified.<ref name=LATsimon>{{cite news |title=Navy Yard shooter 'had a pattern of misconduct' |last1=Simon |first1=Richard |last2=Cloud |first2=David S. |last3=Bennett |first3=Brian |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-washington-navy-yard-shootings-20130916,0,6137381.story |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=September 16, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref> At 7:00&nbsp;p.m., officials ruled out the possibility of other shooters, but were still seeking one other person for possible involvement.<ref name=\"'One of the worst things we've seen' - a timeline of Navy Yard shooting\"/>\n\n===Security precautions===\nOn September 16, many roadways and bridges were temporarily closed,<ref name=cnn/> and flights out of [[Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport]] were temporarily suspended.<ref name=\"USAToday\"/> Eight schools were locked down, with the closest, Brent Elementary School, being locked down until 1 PM.<ref name=cnn/> Shortly after 3:00&nbsp;p.m., [[United States Senate]] buildings went on lock-down for about an hour \"out of an abundance of caution\", according to the [[Senate Sergeant at Arms]].<ref name=\"post_updates\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Senate lockdown lifted|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/16/senate-lockdown-over-large-shooting-suspect/|date=September 16, 2013|accessdate=September 16, 2013|author=Stephen Dinan|work=The Washington Times}}</ref> The [[Washington Nationals]] baseball team postponed their scheduled evening game, owing to the proximity of [[Nationals Park]] to the Navy Yard area (the facilities are close enough to [[Navy Yard \u2013 Ballpark (WMATA station)|share a Metro station]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/nationals-journal/wp/2013/09/16/status-of-nationals-braves-game-unclear-after-navy-yard-shootings/|title=Nationals-Braves game canceled after Navy Yard shootings (updated)|last=Kilgore|first=Adam|author2=James Wagner |date=September 16, 2013|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Navy Yard reopened and resumed usual operations on September 19, 2013. Building 197 reopened on February 2, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/at-the-navy-yard-workers-returned-monday-to-the-scene-of-a-rampage-that-killed-12/2015/02/02/305db3ce-a8bb-11e4-a2b2-776095f393b2_story.html|title=At the Navy Yard, workers returned Monday to the scene of a rampage that killed 12|last=Kilgore|first=Matthew|author2=Stabley |date=September 19, 2013|work=[[NBC Washington]]|accessdate=September 19, 2013}}</ref> In October 2013, the Navy announced a repair-and-restoration contract for the building; the contract indicated that \"the repairs shall be done in a manner that changes the feel, finish, appearance and layout of the space, creating a different sense of place and mitigating the psychological and emotional impacts that the facility itself could have on returning occupants\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wjla.com/articles/2013/10/building-197-may-be-renovated-no-final-decision-yet-94927.html |title=Navy Yard Building 197 may be renovated, no final decision yet |agency=Associated Press |date=October 4, 2013 |publisher=WJLA |accessdate=January 16, 2014}}</ref> The building, renamed after [[Joshua Humphreys]], reopened in 2015. The renovations, costing approximately $44 million, include a reflection area and new visitors' entrance, new flooring and furnishings and an updated cafeteria.<ref>{{cite web|last=Associated Press|title=Navy Yard Shooting: Building 197 will be renamed before reopening|url=http://www.wjla.com/articles/2014/02/navy-yard-shooting-building-197-will-be-renamed-before-reopening-99920.html|publisher=WJLA.com|accessdate=29 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n[[File:Briefing the President on Washington Navy Yard Shootings.jpg|thumb|President Obama receives an update on the shootings investigation from FBI Director [[James Comey]], left, and Attorney General [[Eric Holder]] in the Oval Office on September 17, 2013.]]\nShortly after news of the shooting broke, United States President [[Barack Obama]] pledged to ensure the perpetrators would be held responsible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/video/president-obama-discusses-navy-yard-shooting-20270534|title=President Obama: 'Cowardly Act' at Navy Yard|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=September 16, 2013}}</ref> Obama ordered flags at the [[White House]], all public buildings and all military and naval posts, stations and vessels to be flown at [[half-staff]] until sunset on September 20.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama: Flags To Be Flown At Half-Staff In Wake Of Navy Yard Shooting|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/16/obama-flags-navy-yard-shooting_n_3937236.html|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=September 17, 2013|first=Mollie|last=Reilly|date=September 16, 2013}}</ref>  On September 17, Department of Defense officials laid a wreath at the [[United States Navy Memorial|Navy Memorial plaza]] in honor of the victims.<ref>{{cite news|title=Navy Yard gunman kills 12; dead shooter was contractor|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/17/us/navy-yard-shooting-main/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=September 17, 2013|date=September 18, 2013}}</ref> In the wake of the shooting, President Obama called on Congress to revisit gun control legislation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rucker|first1=Philip|title=Obama calls for gun control in wake of Navy Yard shooting|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2013/09/17/obama-calls-for-gun-control-in-wake-of-navy-yard-shooting/|accessdate=20 October 2015|publisher=Washington Post|date=September 17, 2013}}</ref> On September 22, he attended a memorial service for the victims.<ref>{{cite web|title=Obama to attend memorial service for Navy Yard shooting victims|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/18/obama-attend-memorial-service-navy-yard-shooting-v/|work=The Washington Times|accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe shooting sparked a discussion on the adequacy of security at U.S. military facilities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/bs-md-navy-yard-security-20130916,0,6205343.story|title=Navy Yard shooting reopens debate on base security|last=Fritze|first=John|author2=Matthew Hay Brown |date=September 16, 2013|work=The Baltimore Sun|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref> On September 18, [[Defense Secretary]] [[Chuck Hagel]] ordered a review of security procedures at military facilities around the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hagel orders review of security procedures after Navy Yard massacre|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/18/hagel-orders-review-security-procedures-after-navy/|work=The Washington Times|accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref> ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' magazine reported that virtually anyone with a [[Common Access Card]] (C.A.C.), provided to government contractors, civilian Defense Department employees, and soldiers, can enter many military facilities \"without being patted down or made to go through a metal detector\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/posts/2013/09/16/navy_yard_shooting_highlights_militarys_security_flaws|title=Navy Yard Shooting Highlights Military's Security Flaws|last=Dreazen|first=Yochi|date=September 16, 2013|work=Foreign Policy|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref> The shooter had a [[Security clearance#Secret|Secret]]-level [[security clearance]] and a C.A.C. allowing him to enter the Navy Yard.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/16/suspected-us-shooter-ha_n_3938005.html|title=Aaron Alexis Had 'Secret Clearance,' Employer Says About Washington Navy Yard Suspect|date=September 16, 2013|agency=Reuters|accessdate=September 17, 2013|work=Huffington Post}}</ref> Conservative commentators including [[Alex Jones]], [[Ted Nugent]], and others suggested that \"gun-free zones\" on military bases were to blame for the massacre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mediamatters.org/blog/2013/09/17/the-growing-myth-of-mass-shootings-and-gun-free/195927|title= The Growing Myth Of Mass Shootings And \"Gun-Free Zones\"|work=[[Media Matters for America]]|date=2013-09-17}}</ref> On NBC's ''[[Meet the Press]]'', [[National Rifle Association]] leader [[Wayne LaPierre]] said, \"when the good guys with guns got there, it stopped.\"<ref>[http://presspass.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/09/22/20636650-nras-lapierre-calls-for-more-armed-personnel-after-navy-yard-shooting?lite NRA's LaPierre calls for more armed personnel after Navy Yard shooting], NBC News, September 22, 2013</ref> In the libertarian [[Reason (magazine)|''Reason'' magazine]], J.D. Tuccille said that on domestic U.S. military bases, most soldiers are prohibited from carrying guns, and that this made the base more vulnerable to an attack.<ref>[http://reason.com/blog/2013/09/17/navy-yard-already-suffered-the-restricti Washington Navy Yard Already Suffers the Restrictions That Gun Control Advocates Favor], Reason magazine, September 17, 2013</ref>\n\nOn September 17, gun control activists and relatives of victims of shootings that occurred at [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting|Sandy Hook Elementary School]]; [[2012 Aurora, Colorado shooting|Aurora, Colorado]]; and the [[Wisconsin Sikh temple shooting|Oak Creek, Wisconsin Sikh temple]], came to Washington to protest for stricter gun control. The activists said they hoped that the Navy Yard attack's proximity to [[Capitol Hill]] would motivate lawmakers to act to impose stricter background checks and close the [[gun show loophole]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Colo., Conn. Gun Activists Go to DC After Shooting|url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_24114768/colorado-connecticut-gun-activists-go-dc-after-shooting|work=[[Associated Press]]|date=September 17, 2013|accessdate=September 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2013, Hewlett Packard fired the computer firm The Experts, which employed the shooter, over \"its failure to respond appropriately\" to the Washington Navy Yard shooter's mental health issues.<ref>{{cite web|title=HP fires contracting firm who employed Navy Yard gunman|url=http://investigations.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/09/25/20696197-hp-fires-contracting-firm-who-employed-navy-yard-gunman?lite|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=26 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn October 31 and December 17, 2013, the Senate's [[United States Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs|Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs]] held hearings examining government clearances, background checks, and physical security for federal facilities in the wake of the shootings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo53104|title=The Navy Yard Tragedy: Hearing Before the Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs, United States Senate, One Hundred Thirteenth Congress, First Session: Examining Government Clearances and Background Checks, October 31, 2013; Examining Physical Security For Federal Facilities, December 17, 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn February 20, 2014, a ceremony was held to honor the over 170 law enforcement officers, including 57 D.C. Metropolitan Police officers, who responded and entered the building to search for the shooter. Specifically, MPD Officers Scott Williams and Dorian DeSantis were given the Medal of Valor, U.S. Park Police Medal of Honor, and the Blue Badge Medal for their roles during the gun battle.<ref name=\"HonorsCeremony\"/>\n\nOn December 19, 2014, President Obama signed [[Howard P. \"Buck\" McKeon National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2015|a bill]] authorizing the establishment of a memorial to the shooting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uscode.house.gov/statviewer.htm?volume=128&page=3715|title=Carl Levin and Howard P. \"Buck\" McKeon National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2015|website=uscode.house.gov|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref> A remembrance wall was dedicated the following February.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2015/02/03/remembrance-wall-dedicated-to-12-victims-of-navy-yard-shooting/|title=Remembrance wall dedicated to 12 victims of Navy Yard shooting|last=Brown|first=DeNeen|date=|work=Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Gun violence in the United States]]\n* [[Mass shootings in the United States]]\n*[[List of rampage killers (workplace killings)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category inline|Washington Navy Yard shooting}}\n\n[[Category:2013 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:2013 mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:2013 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in the United States]]\n[[Category:Attacks on government buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Attacks in the United States in 2013]]\n[[Category:Crimes in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2013]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Massacres in the United States]]\n[[Category:Murder in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:September 2013 crimes]]\n[[Category:September 2013 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Navy in the 21st century]]\n[[Category:Washington Navy Yard]]\n[[Category:Workplace violence in the United States]]\n[[Category:2013 in military history]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American mass murder}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n|title            = Washington Navy Yard shooting\n|date             = {{Start date|2013|09|16}}\n|time             = {{nowrap|8:16 a.m. \u2013 9:25 a.m.<ref>{{cite news |title=DC massacre gunman named \u2013 had ex-Navy Yard staffer's ID |last1=Miller |first1=S.A. |last2=Sheehy |first2=Kate |last3=Celona |first3=Larry |url=https://nypost.com/2013/09/16/dc-cops-fbi-probe-shooting-at-washington-navy-yard |newspaper=New York Post |date=September 16, 2013}}</ref><ref name=whathappened>{{cite news |title=Rampage at the Navy Yard: What happened inside Building 197? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/special/local/navy-yard-shooting/scene-at-building-197/ |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=September 20, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref>}}\n|timezone         = EDT\n|type             = Mass murder, shooting, shootout\n|partof           =\n|image            = Alexis Navy Yard 012 1dsLQLVk7nY.jpg\n|image_size       =\n|alt              = CCTV footage of the shooter in building 197 holding a Remington 870 shotgun.\n|caption          = CCTV footage of the shooter in building 197 holding a Remington 870 shotgun.\n|map              =\n|map_size         =\n|map_alt          =\n|map_caption      =\n|location         = NAVSEA Building 197, [[Washington Navy Yard]], [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|coordinates      = {{Coord|38|52|28.7|N|76|59|54.7|W|region:US-DC_type:event_scale:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|injuries         = 8 (3 from gunfire)<ref name=WPmorello>{{cite news |title=Authorities identify seven of the 12 people killed in Navy Yard shooting |last1=Morello |first1=Carol |last2=Hermann |first2=Peter |last3=Williams |first3=Clarence |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/police-search-for-active-shooter-on-grounds-of-washington-navy-yard-in-southeast-dc/2013/09/16/b1d72b9a-1ecb-11e3-b7d1-7153ad47b549_story.html |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=September 16, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref>\n|fatalities       = 13 (including the perpetrator)<ref name=nbcwashington>{{cite news |title=12 Victims Killed, 8 Wounded in Shooting at D.C. Navy Yard, Suspected Gunman Killed |url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/Confirmed-Shooter-at-Navy-Yard-One-Person-Shot-223897891.html |publisher=NBC Washington |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref>\n|perp             = Aaron Alexis\n|weapons          =\n* [[Remington Model 870]] Express Synthetic Tactical 7-Round 12-gauge shotgun<ref name=whathappened/><ref>{{cite web|title=FBI releases terrifying footage of the Navy Yard shooter|url=http://theweek.com/articles/459591/fbi-releases-terrifying-footage-navy-yard-shooter|website=The Week|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Aaron Alexis may have picked up and used victims' weapons: investigators  |last1=Solomon |first1=John |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/16/officers-shooter-may-have-picked-and-used-victimsw/ |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=September 16, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref name=NYTshear>{{cite news |title=Gunman and 12 Victims Killed in Shooting at D.C. Navy Yard |last1=Shear |first1=Michael D. |last2=Schmidt |first2=Michael S. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/17/us/shooting-reported-at-washington-navy-yard.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 16, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref>\n* Stolen [[Beretta M9]] 9mm semi-automatic pistol<ref name=whathappened/><ref name=nbcwashington/>\n|perpetrators     =\n|perpetrator      = Aaron Alexis\n|susperps         =\n|susperp          =\n|numparts         =\n|numpart          =\n|dfens            =\n|dfen             =\n|footage          =\n|motive           =\n}}\n\nThe '''Washington Navy Yard shooting''' occurred on September 16, 2013 when 34-year-old Aaron Alexis fatally shot 12 people and injured three others in a [[mass shooting]] at the headquarters of the [[Naval Sea Systems Command]] (NAVSEA) inside the [[Washington Navy Yard]] in southeast Washington, D.C. The attack took place in the Navy Yard's Building 197; it began around 8:16&nbsp;a.m. EDT and ended when Alexis was killed by police around 9:25&nbsp;a.m. It was the second-deadliest mass murder on a U.S. military base, behind the [[2009 Fort Hood shooting]].\n\n== Details ==\n[[File:Washington Navy Yard shooting Pentagon Channel report.theora.ogv|thumbnail|right|[[Pentagon Channel]] report on the event.]]\n\n===Shooting begins===\nAlexis left his hotel on Monday, September 16 and arrived at the Navy Yard in a rented [[Toyota Prius]] at around 7:53&nbsp;a.m., using a valid pass to enter the Yard.<ref name=NYTshear/><ref name=\"FBI: Navy Yard shooter 'delusional,' said 'low frequency attacks' drove him to kill\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/25/us/washington-navy-yard-investigation/?hpt=us_c2|title=FBI: Navy Yard shooter 'delusional,' said 'low frequency attacks' drove him to kill|date=September 25, 2013|work=CNN|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Photos and video of Navy Yard Shooting released by FBI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.myfoxtwincities.com/story/23528414/photos-and-video-of-navy-yard-shooting-released-by-fbi#ixzz2fxJgXIfX|title=Photos and video of Navy Yard Shooting released by FBI|author=Paul Wagner|date=September 25, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Police after-action report\">{{cite web|url=https://apps.washingtonpost.com/g/page/local/navy-yard-shooting-dc-police-after-action-report/1170/|title=Navy Yard shooting: D.C. police after-action report|work=Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia|date=July 11, 2014}}</ref> As shown on surveillance footage, he entered Building 197 at 8:08&nbsp;a.m. through the main entrance, carrying the disassembled shotgun (the barrel and stock had been sawed off) in a shoulder bag, and he went to the fourth floor where he had conducted work during the prior week. He assembled the shotgun inside a bathroom, then emerged and crossed a hallway into the building's 4 West area, which is a cubicle area near the atrium, the area down below in which workers were having breakfast; he began shooting at 8:16&nbsp;a.m. Six people were hit, five of whom died; the sixth survived wounds to the head and hand.<ref name=whathappened/><ref name=\"Photos and video of Navy Yard Shooting released by FBI\"/><ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Navy Yard shooting: Up to speed in 3 minutes |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/18/us/navy-yard-shooting-recap/index.html?on.cnn=1 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=19 September 2013 |date=September 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921074533/http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/18/us/navy-yard-shooting-recap/index.html?on.cnn=1 |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref> At 8:17&nbsp;a.m.,<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /> the first [[9-1-1]] calls were made.<ref name=whathappened/><ref name=\"Photos and video of Navy Yard Shooting released by FBI\"/><ref name=\"Navy Yard Shooting Timeline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/17/navy-yard-shooting-timeline_n_3940925.html|title=Navy Yard Shooting Timeline|date=September 17, 2013|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBy 8:20&nbsp;a.m., Alexis had shot and killed eight people on the fourth floor, and he made his way to the third floor, where he fatally shot two more people within the next two minutes. He also fired at several people on at least five separate occasions, wounding one woman in the shoulder as she ran up a stairwell. A NAVSEA employee described encountering a gunman wearing all-blue clothing in a third-floor hallway and said that \"he just turned and started firing.\"<ref name=\"Photos and video of Navy Yard Shooting released by FBI\"/><ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /><ref name=\"aljaz\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/americas/2013/09/201391613153627767.html |title=Thirteen killed in US Navy base shooting  |publisher= Al Jazeera |date=September 16, 2013}}</ref> After firing several shots on the third floor, Alexis went to the first floor.<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" />\n\n===Police response===\nOfficers began arriving at 8:23&nbsp;a.m. from the D.C. Metropolitan Police Department and several other law enforcement agencies. There are many buildings on the base, however, and officers were unable to discern Building 197's location, so they asked bystanders for its location. They eventually found Building 197 after moving towards the direction from which people were fleeing. There was confusion regarding the shooting also taking place in a nearby building; in reality, a wounded victim had been evacuated from Building 197 and moved to an area near the second building for medical attention.<ref name=whathappened/><ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /><ref name=\"Navy Yard Shooting Timeline\"/> The United States Capitol Police became embroiled in a controversy when the police union accused the agency of ordering its personnel to stand down and not respond to the shooting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/09/18/navy-yard-capitol-police-swat-team-recalled/2834079/|title=Report: Capitol Police thwarted from aiding at Navy Yard|publisher=|accessdate=September 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhile on the first floor, the shooter moved around randomly before turning around and heading towards the front entrance. He shot and killed Richard Ridgell, the security officer stationed there, and took his 9mm [[Beretta M9]] pistol. Two police officers had asked Ridgell to remain at his post and try to stop the gunman if he attempted to leave the building.<ref name=whathappened/><ref name=nbcwashington/><ref name=NYTshear/><ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /><ref name=foxnews>{{cite news |title=DC gunman was suffering host of mental issues prior to shooting, report says |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2013/09/17/active-shooter-at-washington-navy-yard/ |publisher=Fox News |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Aaron the shooter easily passed two background checks, bought shotgun from Sharpshooters in Lorton, Va.|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/17/aaron-alexis-easily-passed-two-background-checks-b/|work=The Washington Times|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"HonorsCeremony\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/dc-police-honor-courage-dedication-of-navy-yard-massacre-responders/2014/02/21/7894b772-9aee-11e3-ad71-e03637a299c0_story.html |title=D.C. police honor courage, dedication of Navy Yard massacre responders |publisher= Washington Post|date=February 21, 2014 |first=Clarence |last=Williams}}</ref> The shooter then fired his shotgun at a second security guard and a Navy military police officer at the first-floor atrium, missing both; the security guard fired back and the shooter fled down a hallway. Shortly afterwards, the shooter fired at two police officers and a [[Naval Criminal Investigative Service]] agent in another hallway before fleeing again.<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" />\n\nAt 8:34&nbsp;a.m., the shooter went towards the west side of the building, where he encountered two men standing at a corner of the building in an alleyway. He tried to fire at them with his shotgun but realized that he was out of ammunition; he switched to the Beretta, killing one of the men, and the other man escaped without injury.<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /> Reports indicated that the victim in the alleyway was hit by a \"stray bullet\".<ref name=whathappened/> The shooter's use of the pistol in the alleyway led police to initially believe that a second gunman was involved.<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" />\n\n===Death of the shooter===\n<div style=\"float:right; margin:0 0 1.5em 2em; width:20em; border:1px solid #a0a0a0; padding:10px; background:#f5f5f5; font-size:90%;\">\n<div style=\"font-size:120%; text-align:center; font-weight:bold;\">Fatalities<ref>{{cite news |title=Who were the victims of the Navy Yard shooting? |last1=Yan |first1=Holly |last2=Duke |first2=Alan |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/17/us/dc-navy-yard-victims/index.html?hpt=hp_t1 |publisher=CNN |date=September 22, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref name=bp>{{cite news |title=Indian Contractor Vishnu Pandit killed in Washington Navy Yard Shooting |url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2013/09/indian-contractor-vishnu-pandit-killed-in-washington-navy-yard-shooting/ |publisher=Bihar Prabha |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref></div>\n# Michael Arnold, age 59\n# Martin Bodrog, age 53\n# Arthur Daniels, age 51\n# Sylvia Frasier, age 53\n# Kathy Gaarde, age 62\n# John Roger Johnson, age 73\n# Mary Francis Knight, age 51\n# Frank Kohler, age 50\n# Vishnu Pandit, age 61\n# Kenneth Bernard Proctor, age 46\n# Gerald Read, age 58\n# Richard Michael Ridgell, age 52\n</div>\nAfter killing his final victim, Alexis moved to a cubicle area where he discarded the shotgun. At the same time, a team of officers entered Building 197, but they became confused after gunshots echoed through the atrium, leading them to believe that he was on an upper floor. They headed up to the second floor while Alexis remained on the first floor. At approximately 8:55&nbsp;a.m., he went to the third floor and concealed himself inside a bank of cubicles. At 9:12&nbsp;a.m., two officers and two NCIS agents entered the cubicle area<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /> and Alexis opened fire on them, hitting officer Scott Williams in both legs.<ref name=whathappened/><ref name=nbcwashington/><ref name=\"Navy Yard Shooting Timeline\"/><ref name=\"HonorsCeremony\"/> Officer Emmanuel Smith and NCIS agents Brian Kelley and Ed Martin dragged Williams out of the area and alerted other officers to the shooter's presence. Williams was later taken down to the first floor for medical attention, recovering from his wounds.<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" />\n\nAt 9:15&nbsp;a.m., D.C. Police Emergency Response Team officer Dorian DeSantis and U.S. Park Police officers Andrew Wong and Carl Hiott entered the cubicle area and searched the individual banks. Eventually, Alexis jumped out from one of the desks and fired at DeSantis from approximately {{convert|5|ft|spell=in}} away, hitting him twice in his tactical vest, and the three officers returned fire.  DeSantis was uninjured by the gunshot.<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /> At 9:25&nbsp;a.m., DeSantis shot him in the head, and his death was confirmed at 11:50&nbsp;a.m.<ref name=whathappened/><ref name=\"Photos and video of Navy Yard Shooting released by FBI\"/><ref name=\"Navy Yard Shooting Timeline\"/><ref name=\"HonorsCeremony\"/><ref name=\"yahoonewssept17\">{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/13-killed-washington-navy-yard-shooting-rampage-212545654.html |title=13 killed in Washington Navy Yard shooting rampage |publisher= [[Associated Press]] via [[Yahoo News]]|date=September 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"'One of the worst things we've seen' - a timeline of Navy Yard shooting\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/16/us/dc-navy-yard-tic-toc/?hpt=po_c1|title='One of the worst things we've seen' - a timeline of Navy Yard shooting|date=September 16, 2013|work=CNN|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Victims===\nThere were 13 fatalities, including Alexis. He and 11 of the victims were killed at the scene,<ref>{{cite news|title=At least 13 dead in Navy Yard shooting, 14 injured|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/police-search-for-active-shooter-on-grounds-of-washington-navy-yard-in-southeast-dc/2013/09/16/b1d72b9a-1ecb-11e3-b7d1-7153ad47b549_story.html|work=The Washington Post|first= Carol|last=Morello|first2=Peter|last2=Hermann|first3=Clarence Williams|last3=Joseph|accessdate=September 16, 2013|date=September 16, 2013}}</ref> while 61 year-old Vishnu Pandit died at [[George Washington University Hospital]].<ref name=NYTshear/><ref name=\"'I felt him breathe': Survivor of Washington Navy Yard shooting talks about trying to save life of Vishnu Pandit, a co-worker killed during massacre\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/survivor-recalls-save-washington-navy-yard-victim-article-1.1462479|title='I felt him breathe': Survivor of Washington Navy Yard shooting talks about trying to save life of Vishnu Pandit, a co-workers killed during massacre; none of them serving in the army.|work=NY Daily News|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref> All the victims were civilian employees or contractors.<ref name=NYTshear/> Eight others were injured, three of them from gunfire. Police officer Scott Williams and two female civilians were wounded by gunfire and were in critical condition at [[Washington Hospital Center]].<ref name=\"yahoonewssept17\"/><ref name=\"USAToday\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/todayinthesky/2013/09/16/dc-flights-disrupoted-after-navy-yard-shooting/2819899/|title=D.C. departures resume after Navy Yard shooting|last=Mutzabaugh|first=Ben|work=USA Today|accessdate=September 16, 2013|date=September 16, 2013}}</ref><ref name=cnn>{{cite news|title='Multiple' deaths in Navy Yard shooting rampage; suspects may be on loose|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/16/us/dc-navy-yard-gunshots/index.html?hpt=hp_t1|publisher=CNN|first= Barbara|last=Starr|first2=Catherine E.|last2=Shoichet|date=September 16, 2013|accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\n{{anchor|Suspect|Aaron Alexis}}\n{{Infobox mass murderer\n| name        = Aaron Alexis\n| image       = Aaron Alexis-FBI Image.jpg\n| image_size  = 220\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  =\n| occupation  = Civilian contractor, U.S. Navy sailor\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1979|5|9}}\n| birth_place = [[Queens]], [[New York City]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2013|9|16|1979|5|9}}\n| death_place = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| cause       = Gunshot wound to the head during a shootout with police.<ref name=whathappened/>\n| nationality = American\n| motive      =\n}}\n[[File:Video Footage of Shooter at Washington Navy Yard - YouTube.theora.ogv|thumbnail|right|CCTV video of Alexis in the Navy Yard.]]\nAlexis was born May 9, 1979<ref name=whoisaaron/> in the [[New York City]] borough of [[Queens]]. He grew up in [[Brooklyn]] and was a resident of [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]], Texas.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/09/16/up-to-speed-5-things-to-know-about-navy-yard-shooter-aaron-alexis.html | title =Up to Speed: What We Know About Navy Yard Shooter Aaron Alexis | author =Nina Strochlic | publisher =thedailybeast.com | date =September 16, 2013}}</ref> He joined the Navy in May 2007<ref name=\"Police after-action report\" /> and served in Fleet Logistics Support Squadron 46 at [[Naval Air Station Joint Reserve Base Fort Worth]].<ref name =\"AlexisNavy\">{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/09/16/aaron-alexis-navy-yard-shooter/2822731/ | title =Aaron Alexis, Navy Yard shooting suspect: Who is he? |author1=Kevin Johnson |author2=Rick Jervis |author3=Richard Wolf | work =[[USA Today]] | date =September 16, 2013}}</ref> His rating was aviation electrician's mate and he had attained the rank of petty officer third class when he was honorably discharged from the Navy on January 31, 2011, although the Navy originally intended for him to receive a general discharge.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/17/us/navy-yard-suspect/ | title=2008 arrest led to Washington Navy Yard shooter Aaron Alexis' Navy discharge |author1=Mariano Castillo |author2=Chelsea J. Carter | date =September 17, 2013 | work=CNN}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a Navy official, Alexis was cited on at least eight occasions for misconduct.<ref>{{cite news|title=More on Aaron Alexis's time in the Navy|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/liveblog-live/liveblog/shooting-at-washington-navy-yard/?Post+generic=%3Ftid%3Dsm_twitter_washingtonpost#3e136c0b-c174-4b53-9ba4-cfc9d4a14733|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref> In 2010, he was arrested in Fort Worth for discharging a weapon within city limits.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aaron Alexis identified as Washington Navy Yard shooter |url=http://www.baltimorenewsjournal.com/2013/09/16/aaron-alexis-shooter/|publisher=BaltimoreNewsJournal.com|accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nbcdfw.com/news/local/Aaron-Alexis-Fort-Worth-Arrest-Report-223953911.html|title=Aaron Alexis' Fort Worth Arrest Report|author=Frank Heinz|publisher=NBC DFW News| date=September 16, 2013}}</ref> He was also arrested in 2004 in [[Seattle]], Washington for malicious mischief after shooting out the tires of another man's vehicle in what he described as an anger-fueled \"blackout\";<ref name=whoisaaron>{{cite web | url=http://www.myfoxny.com/story/23445925/who-is-aaron-alexis | title =Who is Aaron Alexis? | author =Das, Arun Kirstian | publisher =[[MY Fox NY]] | date =September 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/today/2013/09/washington-navy-yard-shooter-once-lived-in-seattle/ | title =SPD: Navy Yard shooter arrested in Seattle in 2004 for shooting | author =John de Leon | work =[[The Seattle Times]] | date =September 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Crary, David|title=Gunman in Navy Yard shooting was in Navy Reserves|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/texas/article/Gunman-in-Navy-Yard-shooting-was-in-Navy-Reserves-4819303.php|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref> and for disorderly conduct in 2008 in [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb County]], Georgia.<ref name=\"WashPost\">{{cite news|author1=Theresa Vargas |author2=Steve Hendrix |author3=Marc Fisher |title=Aaron Alexis, 34, is dead gunman in Navy Yard shooting, authorities say|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/aaron-alexis-34-is-dead-gunman-in-navy-yard-shooting-authorities-say/2013/09/16/dcf431ce-1f07-11e3-8459-657e0c72fec8_story.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=September 16, 2013|date=September 17, 2013}}</ref> None of his arrests led to prosecution.<ref name=\"HuffPostNYCNative\">{{cite news|author1=Weiss, Murray |author2=Fractenberg, Ben |title=Aaron Alexis, New York Native And Alleged DC Gunman, Once Had Rifle Permit From NYPD|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/17/aaron-alexis-new-york-dc-gunman-_n_3940823.html|work=[[Huffington Post]]|date=September 17, 2013|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Professional work===\nAlexis received a secret-level security clearance in March 2008 that was valid for ten years. Following the Navy Yard shooting, it was found that the federal personnel report which led to the clearance's approval did not mention that his 2004 arrest had involved a firearm. Alexis said on his clearance application that he had never been charged with a felony and that he had not been arrested in the last seven years; the personnel report said that he had given these answers because the 2004 charge had been dismissed.<ref name=\"Navy Yard shooter's personnel report left out gun-related details\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-navy-shooter-20130924,0,3834322.story|title=Navy Yard shooter's personnel report left out gun-related details|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>[https://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo46879 Internal Review of the Washington Navy Yard Shooting: A Report to the Secretary of Defense] [[United States Department of Defense]]</ref> This security clearance investigation was conducted by [[USIS (company)|USIS]], the same contractor that had vetted [[Edward Snowden]]. The Department of Justice has filed fraud charges against USIS in a whistleblower case that is filed as ''United States of America ex rel. [[Blake Percival]] vs USIS''.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite web|author=Sakthi Prasad|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/01/23/us-usa-usis-idUSBREA0M0BD20140123 |title=U.S. brings fraud charges against firm that vetted Snowden|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Federal News Radio\">{{cite web|author=Jack Moore|url=http://www.federalnewsradio.com/520/3618119/Background-investigation-fraud-case-against-USIS-moved-to-DC-court |title=Background investigation fraud case against USIS moved to DC court|date=May 8, 2014|accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlexis worked in Japan from September 2012 to January 2013 on the  [[Navy Marine Corps Intranet]] network for an [[HP Enterprise Services]] sub-contracting company called The Experts.<ref name=cnnwhois>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/16/us/navy-yard-suspects/ | title =Who is Aaron Alexis? | author =Chelsea J. Carter, Ed Lavandera, Evan Perez | publisher =CNN | date =September 16, 2013}}</ref> After returning from Japan, he expressed frustration to a former roommate that he had not been paid properly for the work that he performed.<ref name =\"AlexisNavy\"/><ref name=cnnwhois/> Another roommate said that he would frequently complain about being the victim of discrimination.<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite web|author1=Ackerman, Spencer |author2=Dart, Tom, McVeigh, Karen |title=Aaron Alexis, 34, is dead gunman in Navy Yard shooting, authorities say|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/16/aaron-alexis-washington-navy-yard-shooting|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"wallstreetjournal\">{{cite news|author= Campoy, Ana|title=Friend Says Alexis Was Videogame Fan, Heavy Drinker\n|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2013/09/16/friend-aaron-alexis-skilled-at-shooter-videogames/|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=September 16, 2013|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref> In July 2013, he resumed working for The Experts in the United States.<ref name=cnnwhois/>\n\nAlexis was working on a bachelor's degree in aeronautics from [[Embry\u2013Riddle Aeronautical University, Worldwide]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nola.com/military/index.ssf/2013/09/aaron_alexis_gunman_in_dc_navy.html | title =Aaron Alexis, gunman in D.C. Navy Yard shooting, was 'nice' guy with history of run-ins with police | agency =[[Associated Press]] | publisher =[[The Times-Picayune]] | date =September 16, 2013}}</ref> He was Buddhist.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/16/nation/la-na-navy-shooter-profile-20130917 | work=Los Angeles Times | first1=Molly | last1=Hennessy-Fiske | first2=David | last2=Zucchino | title=Aaron Alexis: An adept Buddhist chanter and an angry man with a gun | date=September 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/19/aaron-alexis-spent-night-buddhist-temple_n_3953198.html | work=Huffington Post | title=Alleged Gunman Said He Couldn't Sleep In Hotel Due To Noises In His Head | date=September 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Friends Describe Navy Yard Gunman as 'Very Polite' Buddhist Who Loved to Meditate|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/friends-describe-navy-yard-gunman-as-very-polite-buddhist-who-loved-to-meditate/|publisher=Mediaite|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Mental health issues===\nAfter the Navy Yard shooting, the media speculated that Alexis had appeared to be suffering from [[mental illness]]. The media reported that Alexis had filed a police report in Rhode Island on August 2, 2013, in which he claimed to be the victim of harassment and that he was hearing voices in his head.<ref>Eric Tucker 18 September 2013. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/18/aaron-alexis-microwave-machine_n_3946916.html Aaron Alexis, Navy Yard Shooting Suspect, Thought People Followed Him With Microwave Machine]. ''The Huffington Post.'' Retrieved: 22 September 2013.</ref> According to an FBI official after the shooting, Alexis was under the \"belief that he was being controlled or influenced by [[Extremely low frequency|extremely low frequency electromagnetic waves]]\". A message later obtained by federal authorities from Alexis's personal computing devices said, \"Ultra low frequency attack is what I've been subject to for the last 3 months. And to be perfectly honest, that is what has driven me to this.\"<ref name=lowfrequency>Greg Botelho and Joe Sterling. September 26, 2013. [http://edition.cnn.com/2013/09/25/us/washington-navy-yard-investigation/?hpt=us_c2 FBI: Navy Yard shooter 'delusional,' said 'low frequency attacks' drove him to kill]. ''CNN.'' Retrieved: 26 September 2013.</ref>\n\nOn August 4, 2013, naval police were called to Alexis's hotel at [[Naval Station Newport]] and found that he had \"taken apart his bed, believing someone was hiding under it, and observed that Alexis had taped a microphone to the ceiling to record the voices of people that were following him\". At the time of the incident, he was working for the contractor at the base.<ref name=\"Report: Concerns about Navy Yard shooter never reported\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/03/18/navy-yard-shooter-called-insider-threat/6558373/|title=Report: Concerns about Navy Yard shooter never reported|author=Tom Vanden Brook, USA TODAY|date=March 18, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 23, Alexis showed up at a [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], Rhode Island, emergency room complaining of [[insomnia]], and he was prescribed 50 milligrams of [[trazodone]], a [[serotonin antagonist and reuptake inhibitor]] [[antidepressant]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wjla.com/articles/2014/01/aaron-alexis-navy-yard-shooter-fooled-veterans-affairs-doctors-99768.html|title=Aaron Alexis, Navy Yard shooter, fooled Veterans Affairs doctors|work=WJLA|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref> Five days late, he sought treatment for insomnia in the emergency room of a VA medical center in Washington, D.C. where he told doctors he was not depressed and was not thinking of harming others. He was given 10 more tablets of trazodone.<ref>Steve Vogel, Sari Horwitz and David A. Fahrenthold. 19 September 2013. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/navy-yard-gunman-aaron-alexis-told-va-doctors-he-was-not-thinking-of-harming-others/2013/09/18/aee01b22-20a6-11e3-b73c-aab60bf735d0_story.html Navy Yard gunman Aaron Alexis told VA doctors he was not thinking of harming others]. ''The Washington Post.'' Retrieved: 19 September 2013.</ref>\n\n===Prior to the shooting===\nAt the time of the shooting, Alexis had been working for a subcontractor on a [[Hewlett-Packard]] Enterprise Services contract supporting a Navy Marine Corps (NMCI) computer network.<ref name=\"foxnews\"/> Alexis arrived in the Washington, D.C., area on or around August 25, 2013, and stayed at various hotels. At the time of the massacre, he had been staying with five other civilian contractors at a [[Residence Inn]] hotel in southwest Washington D.C. since September 7.<ref name=foxnews/><ref>{{cite news |title=FBI: Alexis acted alone, had only one weapon, arrived in D.C. 3 weeks ago |last1=Wolfgang |first1=Ben |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/17/fbi-alexis-acted-alone-had-only-one-weapon-arrived/ |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn Saturday, September 14, two days before the massacre, Alexis visited the Sharpshooters Small Arms Range in [[Lorton, Virginia|Lorton]], Virginia, {{convert|15|mi}} south of Washington. He tested an [[AR-15]] [[semiautomatic rifle]] but did not seek to buy it, a lawyer for the store said. After testing the rifle, Alexis inquired about buying a [[handgun]] at the store, but was told federal law does not allow dealers to sell such guns directly to out-of-state customers. Alexis instead purchased a [[Remington 870]] Express Tactical 12-gauge shotgun and two boxes of shells, after passing a state and federal background check.<ref>{{cite news |title=Inside Sharpshooters, the Newington gun store where Aaron Alexis bought his shotgun |last1=Jackman |first1=Tom |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/local/wp/2013/09/18/inside-sharpshooters-the-newington-gun-store-where-aaron-alexis-bought-his-shotgun/ |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=September 18, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=MILLER: New York Times gets it wrong, media obsessed with linking AR-15 with Navy Yard shooter |last1=Miller |first1=Emily |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/17/miller-new-york-times-gets-it-wrong-about-navy-yar/ |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=MILLER: New York Times corrects AR-15 Navy Yard story, still misses the mark |last1=Miller |first1=Emily |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/20/new-york-times-corrects-ar-15-navy-yard-story-stil/ |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=September 20, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='NYT' Corrects D.C. Shooter/AR-15 Story\u2014But Key Claim Remains |last1=Mitchell |first1=Greg |url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/176280/did-navy-yard-shooter-aaron-alexis-try-buy-ar-15-virginia |newspaper=The Nation |date=September 20, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Report: Navy Yard Shooter Aaron Alexis Test-Fired AR-15, State Law Prevented Purchase |last1=Christopher |first1=Tommy |url=http://www.mediaite.com/print/report-navy-yard-shooter-aaron-alexis-test-fired-ar-15-state-law-prevented-purchase/ |publisher=Mediaite |date=September 18, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref>  Before the shooting, Alexis sawed off the shotgun and scratched the phrases \"Better off this way!\", \"My [[Extremely low frequency|ELF]] weapon!\", \"Not what yall say!\", and \"End to the torment!\" onto the gun's [[Receiver (firearms)|receiver]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Washington Navy Yard shooter believed he was controlled by electromagnetic waves, FBI says as new images released |last1=Asseo|first1=Laurie|last2=Lerman|first2=David|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/washington-navy-yard-shooter-believed-he-was-controlled-by-electromagnetic-waves-fbi-says-as-new-images-released|newspaper=National Post |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=August 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Hagel lays wreath at Navy Memorial - 2013-09-17.jpg|thumb|left|Defense Secretary Chuck Hagel and others lay a wreath at the Navy Memorial on September 17 in honor of the victims.]]\n\n===Reports of other shooters===\nOn the day of the shooting, Washington Chief of Police [[Cathy L. Lanier]] initially said that police were searching for a white male wearing khaki military fatigues and a beret, who had allegedly been seen with a handgun, and a black male wearing olive military fatigues and carrying a [[long gun]].<ref>{{cite web|title=At least 10 wounded in Washington Navy Yard shooting; multiple fatalities|url=https://news.yahoo.com/shots-fired-at-washington-navy-yard--u-s--navy-confirms-130407614.html|publisher=Yahoo News|first=Chris|last= Moody|first2= Dylan|last2=Stableford|accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref> The white male was later identified and deemed not to be a suspect.<ref name=guardian>{{cite news |title=Washington DC shooting: Aaron Alexis named as navy yard gunman \u2013 as it happened |last1=Gabbatt |first1=Adam |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2013/sep/16/washington-dc-navy-yard-shooting-live |newspaper=The Guardian |date=September 16, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"post_updates\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/police-search-for-active-shooter-on-grounds-of-washington-navy-yard-in-southeast-dc/2013/09/16/b1d72b9a-1ecb-11e3-b7d1-7153ad47b549_story.html|date=September 16, 2013 |title=At least 13 dead in Navy Yard shooting; possible suspect at large |author1=Carol Morello, Peter Hermann  |author2=Clarence Williams  |lastauthoramp=yes |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The black male was not identified.<ref name=LATsimon>{{cite news |title=Navy Yard shooter 'had a pattern of misconduct' |last1=Simon |first1=Richard |last2=Cloud |first2=David S. |last3=Bennett |first3=Brian |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-washington-navy-yard-shootings-20130916,0,6137381.story |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=September 16, 2013 |accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref> At 7:00&nbsp;p.m., officials ruled out the possibility of other shooters, but were still seeking one other person for possible involvement.<ref name=\"'One of the worst things we've seen' - a timeline of Navy Yard shooting\"/>\n\n===Security precautions===\nOn September 16, many roadways and bridges were temporarily closed,<ref name=cnn/> and flights out of [[Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport]] were temporarily suspended.<ref name=\"USAToday\"/> Eight schools were locked down, with the closest, Brent Elementary School, being locked down until 1 PM.<ref name=cnn/> Shortly after 3:00&nbsp;p.m., [[United States Senate]] buildings went on lock-down for about an hour \"out of an abundance of caution\", according to the [[Senate Sergeant at Arms]].<ref name=\"post_updates\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Senate lockdown lifted|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/16/senate-lockdown-over-large-shooting-suspect/|date=September 16, 2013|accessdate=September 16, 2013|author=Stephen Dinan|work=The Washington Times}}</ref> The [[Washington Nationals]] baseball team postponed their scheduled evening game, owing to the proximity of [[Nationals Park]] to the Navy Yard area (the facilities are close enough to [[Navy Yard \u2013 Ballpark (WMATA station)|share a Metro station]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/nationals-journal/wp/2013/09/16/status-of-nationals-braves-game-unclear-after-navy-yard-shootings/|title=Nationals-Braves game canceled after Navy Yard shootings (updated)|last=Kilgore|first=Adam|author2=James Wagner |date=September 16, 2013|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Navy Yard reopened and resumed usual operations on September 19, 2013. Building 197 reopened on February 2, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/at-the-navy-yard-workers-returned-monday-to-the-scene-of-a-rampage-that-killed-12/2015/02/02/305db3ce-a8bb-11e4-a2b2-776095f393b2_story.html|title=At the Navy Yard, workers returned Monday to the scene of a rampage that killed 12|last=Kilgore|first=Matthew|author2=Stabley |date=September 19, 2013|work=[[NBC Washington]]|accessdate=September 19, 2013}}</ref> In October 2013, the Navy announced a repair-and-restoration contract for the building; the contract indicated that \"the repairs shall be done in a manner that changes the feel, finish, appearance and layout of the space, creating a different sense of place and mitigating the psychological and emotional impacts that the facility itself could have on returning occupants\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wjla.com/articles/2013/10/building-197-may-be-renovated-no-final-decision-yet-94927.html |title=Navy Yard Building 197 may be renovated, no final decision yet |agency=Associated Press |date=October 4, 2013 |publisher=WJLA |accessdate=January 16, 2014}}</ref> The building, renamed after [[Joshua Humphreys]], reopened in 2015. The renovations, costing approximately $44 million, include a reflection area and new visitors' entrance, new flooring and furnishings and an updated cafeteria.<ref>{{cite web|last=Associated Press|title=Navy Yard Shooting: Building 197 will be renamed before reopening|url=http://www.wjla.com/articles/2014/02/navy-yard-shooting-building-197-will-be-renamed-before-reopening-99920.html|publisher=WJLA.com|accessdate=29 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n[[File:Briefing the President on Washington Navy Yard Shootings.jpg|thumb|President Obama receives an update on the shootings investigation from FBI Director [[James Comey]], left, and Attorney General [[Eric Holder]] in the Oval Office on September 17, 2013.]]\nShortly after news of the shooting broke, United States President [[Barack Obama]] pledged to ensure the perpetrators would be held responsible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/video/president-obama-discusses-navy-yard-shooting-20270534|title=President Obama: 'Cowardly Act' at Navy Yard|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=September 16, 2013}}</ref> Obama ordered flags at the [[White House]], all public buildings and all military and naval posts, stations and vessels to be flown at [[half-staff]] until sunset on September 20.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama: Flags To Be Flown At Half-Staff In Wake Of Navy Yard Shooting|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/16/obama-flags-navy-yard-shooting_n_3937236.html|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=September 17, 2013|first=Mollie|last=Reilly|date=September 16, 2013}}</ref>  On September 17, Department of Defense officials laid a wreath at the [[United States Navy Memorial|Navy Memorial plaza]] in honor of the victims.<ref>{{cite news|title=Navy Yard gunman kills 12; dead shooter was contractor|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/17/us/navy-yard-shooting-main/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=September 17, 2013|date=September 18, 2013}}</ref> In the wake of the shooting, President Obama called on Congress to revisit gun control legislation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rucker|first1=Philip|title=Obama calls for gun control in wake of Navy Yard shooting|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2013/09/17/obama-calls-for-gun-control-in-wake-of-navy-yard-shooting/|accessdate=20 October 2015|publisher=Washington Post|date=September 17, 2013}}</ref> On September 22, he attended a memorial service for the victims.<ref>{{cite web|title=Obama to attend memorial service for Navy Yard shooting victims|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/18/obama-attend-memorial-service-navy-yard-shooting-v/|work=The Washington Times|accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe shooting sparked a discussion on the adequacy of security at U.S. military facilities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/bs-md-navy-yard-security-20130916,0,6205343.story|title=Navy Yard shooting reopens debate on base security|last=Fritze|first=John|author2=Matthew Hay Brown |date=September 16, 2013|work=The Baltimore Sun|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref> On September 18, [[Defense Secretary]] [[Chuck Hagel]] ordered a review of security procedures at military facilities around the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hagel orders review of security procedures after Navy Yard massacre|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/18/hagel-orders-review-security-procedures-after-navy/|work=The Washington Times|accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref> ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' magazine reported that virtually anyone with a [[Common Access Card]] (C.A.C.), provided to government contractors, civilian Defense Department employees, and soldiers, can enter many military facilities \"without being patted down or made to go through a metal detector\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/posts/2013/09/16/navy_yard_shooting_highlights_militarys_security_flaws|title=Navy Yard Shooting Highlights Military's Security Flaws|last=Dreazen|first=Yochi|date=September 16, 2013|work=Foreign Policy|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref> The shooter had a [[Security clearance#Secret|Secret]]-level [[security clearance]] and a C.A.C. allowing him to enter the Navy Yard.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/16/suspected-us-shooter-ha_n_3938005.html|title=Aaron Alexis Had 'Secret Clearance,' Employer Says About Washington Navy Yard Suspect|date=September 16, 2013|agency=Reuters|accessdate=September 17, 2013|work=Huffington Post}}</ref> Conservative commentators including [[Alex Jones]], [[Ted Nugent]], and others suggested that \"gun-free zones\" on military bases were to blame for the massacre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mediamatters.org/blog/2013/09/17/the-growing-myth-of-mass-shootings-and-gun-free/195927|title= The Growing Myth Of Mass Shootings And \"Gun-Free Zones\"|work=[[Media Matters for America]]|date=2013-09-17}}</ref> On NBC's ''[[Meet the Press]]'', [[National Rifle Association]] leader [[Wayne LaPierre]] said, \"when the good guys with guns got there, it stopped.\"<ref>[http://presspass.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/09/22/20636650-nras-lapierre-calls-for-more-armed-personnel-after-navy-yard-shooting?lite NRA's LaPierre calls for more armed personnel after Navy Yard shooting], NBC News, September 22, 2013</ref> In the libertarian [[Reason (magazine)|''Reason'' magazine]], J.D. Tuccille said that on domestic U.S. military bases, most soldiers are prohibited from carrying guns, and that this made the base more vulnerable to an attack.<ref>[http://reason.com/blog/2013/09/17/navy-yard-already-suffered-the-restricti Washington Navy Yard Already Suffers the Restrictions That Gun Control Advocates Favor], Reason magazine, September 17, 2013</ref>\n\nOn September 17, gun control activists and relatives of victims of shootings that occurred at [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting|Sandy Hook Elementary School]]; [[2012 Aurora, Colorado shooting|Aurora, Colorado]]; and the [[Wisconsin Sikh temple shooting|Oak Creek, Wisconsin Sikh temple]], came to Washington to protest for stricter gun control. The activists said they hoped that the Navy Yard attack's proximity to [[Capitol Hill]] would motivate lawmakers to act to impose stricter background checks and close the [[gun show loophole]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Colo., Conn. Gun Activists Go to DC After Shooting|url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_24114768/colorado-connecticut-gun-activists-go-dc-after-shooting|work=[[Associated Press]]|date=September 17, 2013|accessdate=September 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2013, Hewlett Packard fired the computer firm The Experts, which employed the shooter, over \"its failure to respond appropriately\" to the Washington Navy Yard shooter's mental health issues.<ref>{{cite web|title=HP fires contracting firm who employed Navy Yard gunman|url=http://investigations.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/09/25/20696197-hp-fires-contracting-firm-who-employed-navy-yard-gunman?lite|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=26 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn October 31 and December 17, 2013, the Senate's [[United States Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs|Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs]] held hearings examining government clearances, background checks, and physical security for federal facilities in the wake of the shootings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo53104|title=The Navy Yard Tragedy: Hearing Before the Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs, United States Senate, One Hundred Thirteenth Congress, First Session: Examining Government Clearances and Background Checks, October 31, 2013; Examining Physical Security For Federal Facilities, December 17, 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn February 20, 2014, a ceremony was held to honor the over 170 law enforcement officers, including 57 D.C. Metropolitan Police officers, who responded and entered the building to search for the shooter. Specifically, MPD Officers Scott Williams and Dorian DeSantis were given the Medal of Valor, U.S. Park Police Medal of Honor, and the Blue Badge Medal for their roles during the gun battle.<ref name=\"HonorsCeremony\"/>\n\nOn December 19, 2014, President Obama signed [[Howard P. \"Buck\" McKeon National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2015|a bill]] authorizing the establishment of a memorial to the shooting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uscode.house.gov/statviewer.htm?volume=128&page=3715|title=Carl Levin and Howard P. \"Buck\" McKeon National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2015|website=uscode.house.gov|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref> A remembrance wall was dedicated the following February.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2015/02/03/remembrance-wall-dedicated-to-12-victims-of-navy-yard-shooting/|title=Remembrance wall dedicated to 12 victims of Navy Yard shooting|last=Brown|first=DeNeen|date=|work=Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Gun violence in the United States]]\n* [[Mass shootings in the United States]]\n*[[List of rampage killers (workplace killings)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category inline|Washington Navy Yard shooting}}\n\n[[Category:2013 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:2013 mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:2013 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in the United States]]\n[[Category:Attacks on government buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Attacks in the United States in 2013]]\n[[Category:Crimes in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2013]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Massacres in the United States]]\n[[Category:Murder in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:September 2013 crimes]]\n[[Category:September 2013 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Navy in the 21st century]]\n[[Category:Washington Navy Yard]]\n[[Category:Workplace violence in the United States]]\n[[Category:2013 in military history]]\n", "name_user": "90.206.29.254", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Washington_Navy_Yard_shooting"}
